# Workflow Pragmatism

Default behaviors of the tooling (IDE, git wrappers, hooks, CI, platform
defaults) are accepted as long as they do not block development.

## Principles

- **Flow over purity.** If something works by default and does not impede
  progress, leave it alone. Do not spend effort on cosmetic fixes.
- **Fight only real blockers.** Change defaults only when they cause bugs,
  data loss, security issues, or a visibly worse user experience.
- **Stay inside the grain of the tool.** Prefer idiomatic, light-touch
  solutions over clever workarounds.

## Concrete examples

- Automatically appended commit trailers (e.g. `Made-with: Cursor`),
  default formatter output, auto-added imports, noise lines in tool logs
  — ignore unless the user explicitly objects.
- Do not rewrite git history just to clean up such cosmetics.
- Do not introduce custom scripts to suppress harmless default messages.

## When in doubt

Ask the user: "This is the default behavior of <tool>. It doesn't block
anything. Keep it or override?" — then proceed accordingly.
